                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d259">
                <head>No. 204.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Smyth</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Blaine</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Monrovia, Liberia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-10-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 29, 1881</date>. (Received December
                        2.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 153.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The German corvette Victoria, from Eio de
                    Janeiro, arrived here October 28, 1881. The object of the present visit is to
                    demand payment of the promised indemnity in the matter of the German ship
                    Carlos.</p>
                <p>Application for payment having been made by the German consul some time ago, and
                    disregarded, the information was given the foreign office, which is the cause of
                    the presence of the Victoria. This information I have from Commander Von
                    Valois.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JNO. H. SMYTH.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
